# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Caddy — edge TLS for the SaaS (CHR-177)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Two certificate strategies, one reverse proxy:
#
#   1. Platform subdomains ({slug}.churchapp.io) — a single *wildcard* cert
#      (`*.churchapp.io`) obtained once via the ACME DNS-01 challenge covers
#      every church, so no per-signup issuance and no rate-limit exposure.
#
#   2. Church custom domains (www.eglise.org) — issued *on demand* the first time
#      the domain is requested. `on_demand_tls { ask … }` calls the church-api
#      authorization gate first, so Caddy only ever issues a cert for a hostname
#      we recognise (a verified custom domain); unknown hosts are refused, which
#      stops anyone from pointing a domain at the edge to force ACME issuance.
#
# The proxy target (churchapp_web) is the Next.js app, which resolves the request
# Host to a tenant via GET /api/platform/resolve (CHR-144).
#
# Wildcard DNS / ingress (CHR-193): point ONE wildcard record at the edge so a new
# church is reachable the moment it signs up — no per-tenant DNS change:
#   *.churchapp.io   A/AAAA  ->  <edge public IP>     (or CNAME -> the load balancer)
#   churchapp.io     A/AAAA  ->  <edge public IP>
# Church custom domains are CNAME'd to churchapp.io by the church (CHR-176) and get
# an on-demand cert here (CHR-177). Behind Kubernetes, expose this Caddy as the
# ingress with `*.churchapp.io` in the Ingress `tls.hosts` and the same wildcard DNS.

{
	# ACME contact + the on-demand authorization gate.
	email ops@churchapp.io

	on_demand_tls {
		# church-api returns 2xx only for a verified custom domain (CHR-176/177).
		ask https://api.churchapp.io/api/platform/tls/authorize
		# Be gentle with Let's Encrypt while a domain first propagates.
		interval 2m
		burst 5
	}
}

# --- 1. Platform subdomains: one wildcard cert via DNS-01 -------------------
# Needs a Caddy build with your DNS provider module (e.g. xcaddy … --with
# github.com/caddy-dns/cloudflare) and CF_API_TOKEN in the environment.
*.churchapp.io, churchapp.io {
	tls {
		dns cloudflare {env.CF_API_TOKEN}
		resolvers 1.1.1.1
	}
	reverse_proxy churchapp_web:3000
}

# --- 2. Church custom domains: on-demand TLS, gated by the ask endpoint -----
# A catch-all HTTPS site: any host that isn't a platform subdomain lands here and
# gets a certificate on first request — but only if the ask endpoint authorises
# it. Everything else is refused at the TLS handshake.
https:// {
	tls {
		on_demand
	}
	reverse_proxy churchapp_web:3000
}
